06660nam a22008055i 9781442653337DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20171966onc    fo  d z      eng d  a97814426533377 a10.3138/97814426533372doi  a(DE-B1597)479233  a(OCoLC)992453993  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aonccCA-ON 4aHD6961b.I547 1966eb 7aPOL0130002bisacsh04a331.10822300aIndustrial Relations :bChallenges and Responses /ced. by John Crispo. 1aToronto : bUniversity of Toronto Press, c[2017] 4c©1966  a1 online resource (168 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aHeritage00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- tPart I. An International Perspective -- t1. Industrial Relations in the Next Decade -- tPart II. Collective Bargaining in an Age of Change -- t2. Automation and Wage Determination -- t3. Collective Bargaining in Perspective -- t4. Collective Bargaining and the Challenge of Technological Change -- t5. Challenge and Response in the Law of Labour Relations -- tPart III. On the Frontier of Industrial Relations -- t6. The Individual in an Organizational Society -- t7. Government and Poverty -- t8. War on Poverty0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIndustrial relations, which in the past have focused almost entirely on union-management relations, have recently been expanded to include such new areas of interest as manpower and poverty problems. At the University of Toronto a new Centre for Industrial Relations has been established, a research-oriented institution whose primary objective is to further scholarly investigations into all phases of industrial relations. To launch the new Centre a conference was held with distinguished Canadian and international authorities invited to discuss the challenges and responses for Industrial Relations in the next decade, from various points of view. This volume, based on the papers presented, will be a welcome contribution to knowledge in this challenging field. In Part I, "An International Perspective," David A. Morse considers the conference's general theme in terms of its world-wide ramifications. Part II, "Collective Bargaining in an Age of Change," is devoted mainly to a discussion of the impact of industrial change on collective-bargaining institutions and practices. James R. Bright begins with a reminder that there are two schools of thought about the effect of automation upon such variables as skill and wage differentials. Then Frederick Harbison and Arnold R. Weber assess the recent record of collective bargaining: Professor Harbison provides a wide-ranging analysis of the performance of the American collective-bargaining system to date, and Professor Weber describes the effect of technological change upon the respective power of union and management, upon negotiating procedures, and upon the substantive results of collective bargaining. Harry W. Arthurs explores the role of law in coping with change, especially the technological variety. The third part of the volume, "On the Frontier of Industrial Relations," considers two of the many new industrial relations problems: Wilbert E. Moore, discussing the individual in an organizational society, asks for a reconsideration of the roles of institutional responses to the challenges posed by industrialization. Finally, there are two discussions devoted to one of the most pressing economic and social problems: poverty. The Honourable Maurice Sauvé, who, as Canada's Minister of Forestry, is in charge of the Agriculture Rehabilitation and Development Act, discusses the earnest response of governments to the challenge of poverty; Tom Cosgrove, discussing the United States "war on poverty," reviews the dimensions of the challenge posed by poverty in the United States and outlines the federal legislative response to date. These provocative contributions should be received with great interest by representatives of labour, management, and government, as well as by those members of the public who are concerned with the problems of a growing industrial society.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aCollective bargaining. 0aIndustrial relations. 4aDISCOUNT-B. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Labor & Industrial Relations.2bisacsh1 aArthurs, Harry W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBright, James R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCosgrove, Tom, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCrispo, John, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHarbison, Frederick, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMoore, Wilbert E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMorse, David A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSauvé, Maurice, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWeber, Arnold R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press eBook-Package Archive 1933-1999z978311049094740uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144265333740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442653337423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442653337.jpg  a978-3-11-049094-7  University of Toronto Press eBook-Package Archive 1933-1999c1933d1999  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK